The JUnit TestRunner is, by default, in loading mode. That is, modified
classes are reloaded, when runnning the test.
This causes problems when using EJBs in the test cases. A ClassCastException
occurs with the EJB implementation. Different classloaders are used for the
EJB in the test case and the EJB in the application server. To overcome this
problem, disable the loading property in the junit.properties file.

Add a junit.properties file for preference settings. It is stored in the
folder referred to by the &quot;user.home&quot; property. The supported setting is
loading, it can be set to true or false to enable or disable the loading
behavior. 
On Windows 2000, &quot;user.home&quot; could be C:&#92;Documents and Settings&#92;user
A drawback to disabling the loading behavior, is that modified test cases
will require JUnit to be restarted.

Find attached a sample junit.properties file.


Arco.


